%I A394819 #25 Apr 26 2026 17:46:08
%S A394819 1,4,36,552,10320,309600,8688960
%N A394819 Number of distinct permutations generated by Faro and concatenation operations on n equal blocks (saturated case).
%C A394819 SHF(p,q) denotes the set of distinct permutations of p cards generated by expressions built from q ordered blocks Q1,...,Qm (each of size k=p/q) using two binary operations:
%C A394819   +: Concatenation (always defined, non-commutative)
%C A394819   <>: Generalized Faro shuffle. If |A| = l*k and |B| = k, then A <> B is obtained by inserting b_i after each block of l elements of A. If l=1 then it's the regular inner/outer shuffle presented by Diaconis et. al.
%C A394819 Example:
%C A394819 For n=16 and m=4. Q1 = (1 2 3 4) ... Q4 = (13 14 15 16). Q1 + (Q3 <> (Q2 + Q4)) = (1 2 3 4) + ((9 10 11 12) <> (5 6 7 8 13 14 15 16)) is an element of SHF(16, 4) with the induced permutation (1 2 3 4 9 5 6 10 7 8 11 13 14 12 15 16).
%C A394819 If P(p,q) is the set of permutations induced by the expressions of SHF(p, q), for fixed number of blocks n, empirically:
%C A394819  - |P(pk,p)| < |P(p(k+1),p)| for 1<=k<=p-2 (strictly increasing).
%C A394819  - |P(pk,p)| = |P(p(p-1),p)| for p>=3 and k>=p-1.
%C A394819 The group generated by composing the permutations of P(p,q), namely G_{p,q}, forms <I,O> (classical perfect Faro group from Diaconis-Graham-Kantor 1983) when q=2 and contains the group <Im, Om> from Samuel Johnson et al. "A look at generalized perfect shuffles" (2020). G_{2p,p} = S_2p and G_{p,p} = S_p.
%H A394819 Persi Diaconis, R. L. Graham, and William M. Kantor, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/0196-8858(83)90009-X">The mathematics of perfect shuffles</a>, Adv. Appl. Math. 4(2) (1983), 175-196.
%H A394819 Samuel Johnson, Lakshman Manny, Cornelia A. Van Cott, and QiYu Zhang, <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2009.09349">A look at generalized perfect shuffles</a>, arXiv:2009.09349 [math.CO], 2020.
%H A394819 Balbino S. Sobreviela Jiménez, <a href="/A394819/a394819.txt">C++ program to generate a(n)</a>
%F A394819 a(n) = max{|P(n*k, n)|: k >= 1}. If the saturation conjecture is true: a(1) = 1, a(2) = 4, for n>=3: a(n) = |P(n*(n-1), n)|.
%e A394819 For n=3:
%e A394819 For the case with 1 cards per partition card Faro (<>) and Sum (+) become identical so only the permutations of Q1, Q2 and Q3 form different expressions so |SHF(3,3)|=6 but this is not saturation.
%e A394819 For the case with 3-1=2 cards per partition the expression reaches saturation with:
%e A394819 - 6 expressions that permute (a b c): Qa+Qb+Qc
%e A394819 - 6 expressions that permute (a b c): Qa<>(Qb<>Qc)
%e A394819 - 6 expressions that permute (a b c): Qa+(Qb<>Qc)
%e A394819 - 6 expressions that permute (a b c): (Qb<>Qc)+Qa
%e A394819 - 6 expressions that permute (a b c): Qa<>(Qb+Qc)
%e A394819 - 6 expressions that permute (a b c): (Qb+Qc)<>Qa
%e A394819 For a total of |P(6,3)|=a(3)=36 possible permutations.
%o A394819 (C++)
%o A394819 // See program in Links.
%Y A394819 P(n,2) generates groups of order A007346 by composition of permutations.
%K A394819 nonn,hard,more,changed
%O A394819 1,2
